abstract: The barn of S. R. Smith  Co., coal dealers, on East street, New-Haven, Conn., was set on fire yesterday morning at 1 o'clock, and was wholly consumed. Ten horses were saved. The loss is $1,500. Half an hour after the barn was fired the incendiaries fired the spar-shop of H. H. Hanscomb,corner of Ferry and River streets. The building is a total loss, with its contents. Loss $2,000.

abstract: The first meeting of the Saratoga Racing Association having closed yesterday, the bustle and excitement of the past two weeks has given place to a general serenity and quietness thoroughly appreciated by everybody, (always excepting the hotelkeepers.) The trains last night and this morning carried away at least two thousand people, mostly sporting men, who have either gone to Buffalo or New-York to fill the time between the two meetings here.

abstract: It was not very long after the completion of the International Bridge that the Commercial pointed out the necessity for providing still further facilities for crossing the Niagara River at Buffalo. This bridge has but one track, which is mainly occupied by the New-York Central and the Grand Trunk Railways. Other roads are permitted to use it; but they do so only because they cannot help themselves.

abstract: CINCINNATI, Ohio, Aug. 7. The recovery of thirteen bodies lost by the burning of the steamer Pat. Rogers has been reported in these dispatches. Specials from Aurora to-night give nine additional, making twenty-two in all so far recovered. Several bodies are reported recovered near Rising Sun, and now in charge of the Coroner there, but the names are not known.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Aug. 8. Capt. R.A. Torry, of the Thirteenth Infantry, commanding at Camp Brown, Wyoming Territory, reports that Capt. Bates' company made a scout recently and attacked a party of eight Indians about twenty miles south of the Sweet Water, killing one Sioux and capturing seven horses and one mule. One of Capt. Bates' scouts was seriously wounded.

abstract: NEWPORT, R.I., Aug. 8. The Corinthian race did not come off to-day, as there was a heavy storm, which began early in the morning. It blew a gale from the south south-east, and the rain poured down in torrents. The yachtmen remained on board their vessels until this afternoon, kept there by the heavy sea, which rendered the passage of small boats from the fleet to the shore quite dangerous.

There were present deputations from the Eighth, Ninth, Twelfth, Fourteenth, Twenty-second, Seventy-first, and Seventyninth Regiments. The weather was favorable for fine shooting. There was but little wind stirring, and the heat was not so oppressive as it has been for some time previously.

abstract: NEWPORT, R.I., Aug.12. The races for the two club prizes came off to-day. abstract: Perhaps the most striking thing about New- port, at least to one who has always heard of it as a famous place of resort, is the comparative lack of hotel life. A stranger coming here expecting to find hotels by the score and transient guests by the thousand will be grievously disappointed, and go away imagining it to be the dullest and least attractive of watering-places.

abstract: An adjourned meeting of the Nineteenth Assembly District Republican Association was held last evening in Tenth avenue, near Sixty-fifth street, Charles F. Bruder in the chair. The hall was crowded, and great interest was manifested by those present. After some discussion as to the advisability of removing the head-quarters of the association from the present location to the corner of One Hundredth street and Tenth avenue, it was decided that no change should be made.

abstract: This Sabbath upon the camp-ground is a beautiful one. The air is mild, and, although there is not a bright sunlight, old Sol occasionally peeps through the clouds and bathes the surroundings in a flood of warmth. There are perhaps six thousand people roving through the grove, or attending the various meetings, but no more. In fact the number is surprisingly small compared with last year's Sunday statistics.

abstract: LONDON, Aug. 25. The cricket match at Dublin was continued this morning with the Irishmen at the wickets. They finished their first innings with a score of 47. The Americans, who made 71 yesterday, added 94 to the count in their second inning. The Dublin Club then went to the bat for their final inning and completed it with only 31 runs, leaving the Americans the winners by 87.
